<section xml:id="HwTheMengerSponge">
  <title>HOMEWORK: The Menger Sponge and the Mandlebrot Set</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
          <idx><h>HOMEWORK: The Menger Sponge and the Mandlebrot Set</h></idx>
      There are several famous fractals of interest.
      We already saw Sierpinski's Triangle.
      Another one of these is the Menger Sponge.
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="fig_menger">
      <caption>The Menger Sponge</caption>
      <image width="56%" source="images/menger.png"/>
    </figure>
  </introduction>
  <subsection>
    <title>A Few of My Favorite Spaces</title>
    <p>
      Mathematician Evelyn Lamb has written as an incredible series entitled
      <q>A Few of My Favorite Space</q>
      for Scientific American covering different mathematical spaces.
    </p>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Read
          <q>A Few of My Favorite Spaces: The Menger Sponge</q>
          by Evelyn Lamb in Scientific American \cite{menger}.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <p>
      { https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/roots-of-unity/a-few-of-my-favorite-spaces-the-menger-sponge/.}
    </p>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>A Few Questions</title>
    <p>
      After reading Lamb's article,
      address the following questions.
    </p>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          How do you develop the Menger Sponge?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What is the dimension of the Menger Sponge?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What are your thoughts about the Menger Sponge?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>The Mandelbrot Set and Numberphile</title>
    <p>
      Another famous fractal is the Mandelbrot Set shown in <xref ref="fig_mandelbrot">Figure</xref>.
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="fig_mandelbrot">
      <caption>The Mandelbrot Set</caption>
      <image width="56%" source="images/mandlebrot.png"/>
    </figure>
    <p>
      Numberphile is a popular math-related YouTube channel that covers a huge variety interesting high-level mathematics topics.
      Numberphile is a fantastic resource to mathematics students.
      We will look to Numberphile several times in this text.
    </p>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Watch Numberphile's video
          <q>The Mandelbrot Set</q>. \cite{numberphile_mandelbrot}
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <p>
      \link{https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NGMRB4O922I&amp;t=473s }
    </p>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Explain the process that determines whether or not a number will be in the Mandelbrot Set or not.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>
